column1: stream of consciousness well , in other words , free association .
column2: i can accommodate this assignment .
column3: it 's amazing what some of the most ordinary things or objects can really do if studied .
column4: as i was walking home from a stressful day of calculus , chemistry , and psychology , i passed a squirrel searching for food on one of the lawns of a building .
column5: the animal was wandering curiously close to the sidewalk where students were walking .
column6: on normal circumstances , squirrels and other such rodents would run away as fast as possible on first sight of humans .
column7: however , this squirrel continued to hunt for food as i walked by it .
column8: i stopped and watched it , it would insert his nose and mouth into the ground and bite at some apparent food object , try it and eat it if the food object was of any value to the rodent .
column9: curious i continued to watch , wondering what else it would do .
column10: i approached the squirrel , closer and closer .
column11: when i had come too close the squirrel dove into the ground , attempting to camouflage itself with its grassy surroundings .
column12: fantastic !
column13: i never knew that squirrel had the notion of of trying to camouflage or hiding itself .
column14: i had always thought they would run and jump away .
column15: i remained crouched on the sidewalk as i continued to watch this curious little squirrel .
column16: after some time it started slowly approaching me .
column17: i continued to watch it , much like a predator stalking its prey .
column18: without motion or movement i crouched and stared at it .
column19: it came to within 18 inches of me .
column20: how wonderful !
column21: the squirrel was n't afraid to come towards a human .
column22: it remained there for a couple of moments until other pedestrians walked by and frightened the squirrel .
column23: of course during my observation process many people walking to and fro classes walked by me and gave me awkward glances .
column24: i was so completely lost in the amazing little squirrel .
column25: at one point it had left its territory and wandered onto the street , it found a mass of dumped bread .
column26: the rodent gripped a piece with its mouth and ran back across the street to its territory .
column27: once there the squirrel began to eat .
column28: after eating half of the portions , he began digging into the ground trying to find a strategic location to hide the bread .
column29: not finding a place , i began to try to help .
column30: i grabbed a nearby twig and started digging into the ground to make some spots for the squirrel .
column31: i realized i was destroying the landscaping and garden of the lawns of the building .
column32: i was trying to help my new little friend .
column33: finally , after several unsuccessful attempts the squirrel ran up into a tree after being frightened by other people .
column34: i felt anger , why would someone do that , i 'm interacting with this squirrel .
column35: after it ran into the tree , it did n't come back down .
column36: at some point i left .
column37: in retrospect , i think i spent almost 40 minutes observing the squirrel .
column38: i was stressed before beginning my observations and interactions , but afterwards , amazingly , i was calm and i actually had an enjoyable time playing with it .
column39: i also learned quite a bit about the behavior of the squirrel .
column40: i never knew that they were as smart as i observed , i also realized even more what incredible running , jumping and climbing skills those pesky rodents have .
column41: some may have viewed my time spent with the squirrel a complete waste , but it was actually quite relaxing and enlightening .
column42: many new experiences have enlightened me to some of the lesser seen wonders of this world .
column43: a squirrel having so many complexities .
column44: amazing .
column45: what about the human being or the human mind .
column46: the complexities of the mind and brain are endless or almost impossible !
column47: so many questions .
column48: it 's almost mind boggling thinking about what can be so deep or interesting .
column49: wow very very crazy .

column11: procedures : first , obtain the following materials : 2 room temperature agar plates , labeled a and b,1 refrigerated agar plate , labeled c , potassium permanganate solution , methylene blue solution , marking pen , ruler , and pasteur pipettes .
column12: turn the agar plate labeled `` a '' upside down and make two small dots on the bottom of the plate with the marker .
column13: each dot should be at least 2cm from the edge of the plate and at least 3cm away from the other dot .
column14: next to one dot write `` potassium permanganate '' and next to the other dot write `` methylene blue '' .
column15: mark plates `` b '' and `` c '' the same way .
column16: remove the lid from agar plate `` a '' .
column17: using a micropipette , withdraw 10 microliters of potassium permanganate solution and use it to make a small , neat droplet of dye solution directly above the correspondingly labeled dot .
column18: place a similar dot of potassium permanganate solution on plates `` b '' and `` c '' .
column19: use the same procedure to place small , neat drops of methylene blue dye solution on your plates .
column20: keep plates a and b at room temperature , and place plate c back in the refrigerator .
column21: every 15 minutes , determine the diameter of the dye circles .
column22: record your measurements in a table .

column1: why do people always seem to stress out over the most petty and unimportant things ?
column2: it seems as though when we leave the mundane routine of college life and enter the college atmosphere that our perceptions and opinions of people and things become all the more important .
column3: when my roommate and i went shopping at the galleria mall this weekend these petty issues seemed ever present .
column4: girls shopping beside us charging obscene amounts of money onto daddy 's credit cards .
column5: have many teens forgotten about the value and importance of money ?

column7: my new friend kenny happens to be fixated on getting dates'girlfriend and there is this guy in his complex who really likes him .
column8: the entire time at the mall kenny asked my roommate and i if random people were hotter than he was .
column9: this relentless insecurity and constant echo of self degredation was honestly quite draining .
column10: why ca n't people just accept that they are who they are and be happy at that ?

column4: i am actually in the recovery stages right now .
column5: i have been battling this for two years now , have been in the hospital twice , and have had therapy involving nutritional counseling , psychiatry , and group therapy .

column9: the battle is all in my head .
column10: it is my mind that will not `` allow '' me to eat when i am hungry , and it is my mind that tells me i do n't need to gain weight , that i am not critically underweight , and that i am physically in good shape .

column12: my psychiatrist has shed some light on the whole thing , but still no one can completely explain things like this that involve the mind .

column17: ( i think she 's a little partial to the subject myself .

column24: it 's strange how i can think about it realistically and know that i am still not eating enough and then my irrational side of my mind will come in and tell me i am fine and do n't need to gain .
column25: but , as the date comes closer to my appointment , i will start to gradually get more afraid , and get mad at myself for not doing enough .
column26: and still , that wo n't make it any easier to eat a thing .

column28: you wo n't want to do it , you 'll feel incredibly anxious and angry with yourself for letting yourself go .
column29: i have experienced this a few times ( like in the hospital ) , but i have n't been able to do much of this by myself .
column30: it seems like it is n't worth it to let yourself feel so bad when you could just avoid the problem and not feel the anxiety .
column31: instead , by ignoring it , you get to feel hungry , tired , irritable , you get to think about food all the time because of your low body weight , you make your family freak out , you risk losing your car and your opportunity to go to
column32: college .
column33: it seems that the negatives of not eating strongly outweigh the positives of not eaten , and i can logically see that .

column35: i hope i will make it to the point soon .

column37: i am sure everyone thinks i am crazy , but you just ca n't explain to someone how you feel .
